  "text": "One particular computational problem arises when the finite-difference approach is applied to steady isotropic turbulence (which is preferable to decaying turbulence in terms of statical analysis). The most common method for forcing the flow is to apply a forcing to the Navier-Stokes equations for all modes in the wavenumber sphere |k|<k f , often refered to as large-scale forcing. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] employed this approach in their 512 3 gridpoint FDM. In order to appy the forcing, they performed Fourier transformations on the complete velocity field in order to obtain the low-wavenumber components. however, this direct application of the large-scale forcing technique reduces the parallel efficiency in larger-size computations since it requres communication of the whole velocity field.",
